```

This vignette demonstrates `fresh` on a real watershed analysis task: extracting
the stream network upstream of the Neexdzii Kwa (Upper Bulkley River) /
Wedzin Kwa confluence — the same scoping used in the
[restoration_wedzin_kwa_2024](https://github.com/NewGraphEnvironment/restoration_wedzin_kwa_2024)
land cover change analysis.

## Snap the confluence

Start by snapping a point near the Neexdzii Kwa / Wedzin Kwa confluence to the
FWA stream network.

```{r snap}
library(fresh)
library(sf)

mouth <- frs_point_snap(x = -126.18, y = 54.39)
mouth[, c("gnis_name", "blue_line_key", "downstream_route_measure", "distance_to_stream")]
```

In the real analysis, we use the known Bulkley mainstem position directly
(blue_line_key = 360873822, downstream_route_measure = 166030.4) — the same
values used in `lulc_network-extract.R`.

## Extract upstream network

Get all stream segments upstream of the confluence, filtered to order 4+ —
streams large enough to have floodplains.

```{r upstream}
# Known Neexdzii Kwa / Wedzin Kwa confluence on Bulkley mainstem
blk <- 360873822
drm <- 166030.4

upstream <- frs_network_prune(
  blue_line_key = blk,
  downstream_route_measure = drm,
  stream_order_min = 4,
  watershed_group_code = "BULK"
)

nrow(upstream)
sort(unique(upstream$stream_order))
```

```{r plot-network, fig.cap = "Neexdzii Kwa stream network (order 4+), coloured by Strahler stream order."}
plot(
  upstream["stream_order"],
  main = "",
  key.pos = 1,
  key.width = lcm(1.3),
  lwd = upstream$stream_order / 2
)
```

The network contains `r nrow(upstream)` segments across orders
`r paste(sort(unique(upstream$stream_order)), collapse = ", ")`.
Named streams: `r paste(sort(unique(na.omit(upstream$gnis_name))), collapse = ", ")`.

## Fish observations

Query chinook observations in the Bulkley. The `cols` parameter keeps the
result lean — we only need species, date, life stage, and location.

```{r fish-obs}
chin_obs <- frs_fish_obs(
  species_code = "CH",
  watershed_group_code = "BULK",
  cols = c("fish_observation_point_id", "species_code",
           "observation_date", "life_stage", "geom"),
  limit = 100
)

nrow(chin_obs)
table(chin_obs$life_stage)
```

## Custom table and columns

All functions accept `table` and `cols` parameters so you can target any
schema/view and select only the columns you need. For example, to query the
bcfishpass habitat model with specific columns:

```{r custom-table}
habitat <- frs_fish_habitat(
  watershed_group_code = "BULK",
  cols = c("blue_line_key", "gnis_name", "stream_order",
           "channel_width", "gradient", "geom"),
  limit = 20
)

names(habitat)
summary(habitat$channel_width)
```

## Compare with raw SQL

Without `fresh`, the upstream network query requires ~20 lines of SQL: a CTE
to look up the reference segment's ltree codes, a cross join against the full
stream table, and an `fwa_upstream()` boolean filter. See
`restoration_wedzin_kwa_2024/scripts/lulc_network-extract.R` for the raw
version. `frs_network_prune()` wraps this in one function call.

## Summary

| Step | Function | What it does |
|------|----------|-------------|
| Snap | `frs_point_snap()` | Index a point to the nearest stream |
| Fetch | `frs_stream_fetch()`, `frs_lake_fetch()`, `frs_wetland_fetch()` | Retrieve FWA features |
| Traverse | `frs_network_upstream()`, `frs_network_downstream()` | Walk the network |
| Prune | `frs_network_prune()`, `frs_order_filter()` | Filter by order, gradient |
| Fish | `frs_fish_obs()`, `frs_fish_habitat()` | Observations and habitat model |

All functions accept `table` and `cols` parameters — swap the source table or
select only the columns you need.
